# Presentation Layer

The HTTP entry point. Depends only on `application`. Thin: translate HTTP ⇄ use cases.

## Structure

```
presentation/
├── controller/   # REST controllers
├── request/      # Inbound HTTP DTOs (CreateUserRequest, LoginRequest)
└── response/     # Outbound HTTP DTOs (UserResponse, AuthResponse)
```

## Controllers

- Keep them **thin**: validate input, call a use case, map to a response. No business logic.
- Inject use cases via constructor. One controller per resource/aggregate.
- Map request DTO → application command, and application response → HTTP response DTO.

```java
@RestController
@RequestMapping("/api/users")
public class UserController {
    private final CreateUserUseCase createUser;

    public UserController(CreateUserUseCase createUser) { this.createUser = createUser; }

    @PostMapping
    public ResponseEntity<UserResponse> create(@Valid @RequestBody CreateUserRequest request) {
        var result = createUser.execute(request.toCommand());
        return ResponseEntity.status(HttpStatus.CREATED).body(UserResponse.from(result));
    }
}
```

## Request / Response DTOs

- Use `record`s. Validate inbound requests with Jakarta Bean Validation (`@NotBlank`, `@Email`).
- Presentation DTOs are separate from application DTOs and domain models — never expose entities.
- `request` DTOs convert to application **commands**; `response` DTOs are built from application results.

## Error handling

- Centralize with a `@RestControllerAdvice` exception handler (place in a shared/common package).
- Map domain/application exceptions to proper HTTP status + a consistent error body
  (e.g. `EmailAlreadyInUseException → 409`, validation → `400`, not found → `404`).
- Never leak stack traces or internal messages to clients.

## Conventions

- REST URLs: plural nouns, kebab/lowercase (`/api/users`, `/api/users/{id}/confirm`).
- Use correct HTTP verbs and status codes; return `201` on creation with the created resource.
